            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Cole\u2019s life is a testament to quiet, relentless ambition, a story written in the neat columns of a ledger book. The only son of Taiwanese immigrants, he grew up in the suburbs of Fremont, where the scent of fabric softener from his parents\u2019 laundromat was the backdrop to his childhood. They had poured their life savings and endless hours into the business, instilling in David an unwavering belief that success was not a matter of luck, but of disciplined, sustained effort.\n\nHis path was clear from a young age. He excelled in school, trading the chaotic energy of a typical teenage life for the predictable structure of homework and part-time work. Earning his Bachelor's in Business Administration from UC Berkeley was a moment of immense pride, a fulfillment of his parents\u2019 American dream. David immediately entered the consulting world, joining a major firm in San Francisco just before the dot-com bubble burst. Watching fortunes evaporate overnight solidified his professional philosophy: avoid hype, master the fundamentals, and build a reputation on reliability.\n\nFor two decades, David climbed the corporate ladder. A long-term relationship ended in his late thirties, a casualty of 80-hour workweeks and a focus so singular it left little room for another person. Now a Senior Management Consultant, he is the person companies call to streamline operations and solve complex problems. His life mirrors his work: efficient, optimized, and impeccably managed.\n\nHe resides in a minimalist apartment in Rincon Hill, its floor-to-ceiling windows offering a panoramic, yet distant, view of the city he helps shape. His 1.2-mile walk to the Financial District is a cherished daily ritual, a time to clear his head with an economics podcast before a day of high-stakes meetings. Evenings are often spent with a glass of Japanese whisky and industry reports, though he maintains a small circle of long-time professional friends for monthly dinners.\n\nNow at 51, with financial security achieved, David feels a quiet yearning for something less quantifiable. He dreams not of a bigger title, but of leveraging his expertise for a cause, perhaps mentoring young entrepreneurs or serving on the board of an arts non-profit. He hopes to finally travel for pleasure, to see the world not as a series of conference rooms, but as the vast, unstructured place his parents left behind."
